<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
<taxonomicName authority="Montagu, 1808" authorityName="Montagu" authorityYear="1808" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Myxicola" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myxicola infundibulum" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="infundibulum">Myxicola infundibulum (Montagu, 1808)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
Species complex. 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Myxicola" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myxicola infundibulum" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="infundibulum">Myxicola infundibulum</taxonomicName>
is a taxon with a long list of synonyms and has until recently been considered cosmopolitan (
<bibRefCitation author="Giangrande, A." journalOrPublisher="Mediterranean Marine Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="283 - 293" title="Sabellidae (Annelida) from the Faro coastal lake (Messina, Ionian Sea), with the first record of the invasive species Branchiommabairdi along the Italian coast" volume="13" year="2012">Giangrande et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). However, specimens from different parts of the world (West Atlantic, Mediterranean, Pacific Canada) show genetic and morphological differences (
<bibRefCitation author="Carr, Christina May" journalOrPublisher="PLoS ONE" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" title="A tri-oceanic perspective: DNA barcoding reveals geographic structure and cryptic diversity in Canadian polychaetes." volume="6" year="2011">Carr et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Giangrande, A." journalOrPublisher="Mediterranean Marine Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="283 - 293" title="Sabellidae (Annelida) from the Faro coastal lake (Messina, Ionian Sea), with the first record of the invasive species Branchiommabairdi along the Italian coast" volume="13" year="2012">Giangrande et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
found specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Myxicola" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myxicola" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Myxicola</taxonomicName>
from the Gulf of Naples and Lake Faro to morphologically differ from specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Myxicola" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myxicola infundibulum" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="infundibulum">Myxicola infundibulum</taxonomicName>
from the type locality in the North Adriatic Sea. It is therefore possible that the species constitutes a complex of cryptic species even in the Mediterranean.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
